To ensure that all updates across multiple tables are either committed or rolled back as a single unit, you need to use a transaction. Dapper supports transactions through the `IDbTransaction` interface, which you can pass to the `Query` method. If any update fails, you can roll back the transaction using the `Rollback` method. Here's an example:

```c#
public void UpdateMultipleTables(string user, string newRunId)
{
    using (var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
    {
        connection.Open();
        var transaction = connection.BeginTransaction();

        try
        {
            string updateQuery1 = "UPDATE Table1 SET Column1 = @NewRunId WHERE User = @User";
            string updateQuery2 = "UPDATE Table2 SET Column2 = @NewRunId WHERE User = @User";

            var parameters = new { User = user, NewRunId = newRunId };

            connection.Execute(updateQuery1, parameters, transaction);
            connection.Execute(updateQuery2, parameters, transaction);

            // If all updates are successful, commit the transaction
            transaction.Commit();
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            // If any update fails, roll back the transaction
            transaction.Rollback();

            // Handle the exception or rethrow it as needed
            throw;
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `UpdateMultipleTables` method starts a new transaction using the `BeginTransaction` method. Then, the two update queries (`updateQuery1` and `updateQuery2`) are executed using the `Execute` method, passing the transaction object as an argument.

If any update fails and an exception is thrown within the `try` block, the transaction is rolled back using the `Rollback` method. Otherwise, if all updates are successful, the transaction is committed using the `Commit` method.

By encapsulating the updates within a transaction, you can ensure that all updates are either committed or rolled back as a single unit.

If the updates to multiple tables are performed by different DAOs (Data Access Objects) and you need to call them within the same method with a transaction, you can modify the approach slightly. Here's an example:

```c#
public void UpdateMultipleTables(string user, string newRunId)
{
    using (var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
    {
        connection.Open();
        var transaction = connection.BeginTransaction();

        try
        {
            // Call the DAO methods to perform the updates on different tables
            DAO1.UpdateTable1(user, newRunId, connection, transaction);
            DAO2.UpdateTable2(user, newRunId, connection, transaction);

            // If all updates are successful, commit the transaction
            transaction.Commit();
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            // If any update fails, roll back the transaction
            transaction.Rollback();

            // Handle the exception or rethrow it as needed
            throw;
        }
    }
}
```

In this modified example, assume you have two DAO classes, `DAO1` and `DAO2`, responsible for updating different tables. These DAOs should have corresponding methods, `UpdateTable1` and `UpdateTable2`, that accept the necessary parameters along with the `SqlConnection` and `SqlTransaction`.

You can call these DAO methods within the `try` block, passing the connection and transaction objects so that they can participate in the same transaction. If any update fails and an exception is thrown, the transaction will be rolled back. Otherwise, if all updates are successful, the transaction will be committed.

Note: Ensure that all DAO methods `UpdateTable1` and `UpdateTable2` use the same connection and transaction objects passed from the calling method (`UpdateMultipleTables`).

