In PostgreSQL with C#, you can use the `Npgsql` library for database connectivity. When working with transactions in `Npgsql`, you would replace the `SqlTransaction` type with the `NpgsqlTransaction` type. Here's an example of how to define a transaction in PostgreSQL with C#:

```c#
using (var connection = new NpgsqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    connection.Open();

    var transaction = connection.BeginTransaction(); // Start the transaction

    try
    {
        // Perform your database operations and queries using the NpgsqlConnection and NpgsqlTransaction

        transaction.Commit(); // Commit the transaction if everything is successful
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        transaction.Rollback(); // Rollback the transaction if an exception occurs

        // Handle the exception or rethrow it as needed
        throw;
    }
}
```

In the above example, `NpgsqlConnection` is used to establish a connection to the PostgreSQL database, and `connection.BeginTransaction()` starts a new transaction. The transaction object, `NpgsqlTransaction`, represents the active transaction associated with the connection.

Inside the `try` block, perform your database operations using the `NpgsqlConnection`, passing the transaction object to ensure they are part of the same transaction.

If no exceptions occur, you can call `transaction.Commit()` to commit the changes. If an exception is thrown, `transaction.Rollback()` is called to roll back the transaction and undo any changes made within it.

Make sure you have included the `Npgsql` namespace in your code file:

```c#
using Npgsql;
```

Remember to install the `Npgsql` NuGet package in your project for establishing a connection to PostgreSQL.

